Managing python with pyenv
Read from: https://realpython.com/intro-to-pyenv/
https://medium.com/python-every-day/python-development-on-macos-with-pyenv-2509c694a808

To see a list of Python versions
$ pyenv install --list

To install a specific versions
$ pyenv install -v 3.7.2

To look at installation location
$ ls ~/.pyenv/versions/


All of your versions will be located here. This is handy because removing these versions is trivial:
$ rm -rf ~/.pyenv/versions/2.7.15

Of course pyenv also provides a command to uninstall a particular Python version:

$ pyenv uninstall 2.7.15

pyenv versions

To change to s specific version:
pyenv global 2.7.15

Set Local Python
To set a Python version for a specific project, cd into your project and then run:
pyenv local <python-version>

install virtualenv:
python3 -m pip install --user virtualenv

Create a virtual environment with venv (old way. It's harder to give specify which version to use.)
python3 -m venv env
source env/bin/activate
deactivate



pyenv creating virtual environments:
$ pyenv virtualenv <python_version> <environment_name>
$ pyenv virtualenv 3.6.8 myproject
$ pyenv local myproject
$ pyenv which python
pyenv which pip
$ pyenv activate <environment_name>
$ pyenv deactivate
Existing environments can be listed with:
$ pyenv virtualenvs
